{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640288"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17816"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17816"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.76,0,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72524"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10530"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9908"},{"type":"tags","id":"9913"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24603"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72524"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGas exchange in the lungs occurs primarily through diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane. This process is driven by differences in partial pressures between the alveolar air and pulmonary capillary blood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the direction of oxygen diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["From areas of low solubility to high solubility","Equally in both directions until concentrations equalise","From high pressure in alveoli to low pressure in capillaries","Against the concentration gradient using active transport","From high pressure in capillaries to low pressure in alveoli"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOxygen diffuses \u003Cstrong\u003Efrom high pressure in alveoli to low pressure in capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E. The partial pressure of oxygen in alveoli is approximately 100 mmHg, while in deoxygenated pulmonary capillary blood it is approximately 40 mmHg. This pressure gradient drives oxygen diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom areas of low solubility to high solubility\u003C/strong\u003E - Diffusion is driven by partial pressure differences, not solubility gradients.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqually in both directions until concentrations equalise\u003C/strong\u003E - While some bidirectional movement occurs, the net flow is predominantly from alveoli to capillaries due to the pressure gradient.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAgainst the concentration gradient using active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxygen diffusion is a passive process that does not require energy expenditure.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom high pressure in capillaries to low pressure in alveoli\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the opposite direction of the actual oxygen movement.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pressure gradient-driven diffusion is essential for maintaining adequate oxygenation of blood as it passes through the pulmonary circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oxygen diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane occurs down its partial pressure gradient from high (alveoli) to low (capillary blood).","The partial pressure of oxygen in alveoli is approximately 100 mmHg while deoxygenated blood in pulmonary capillaries is approximately 40 mmHg.","Diffusion continues until equilibrium is reached or blood leaves the capillary."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17816"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57994"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T22:13:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T22:14:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10530"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72524"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrie